<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Endangered Species Act</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z Beta">
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor = #ffffff>
<P>

<CENTER>
<TABLE border=0 width=85%>
<TR><TD>
<H1>
<CENTER>
Two Approaches to<BR>
Compensated Takings Under<BR>
the California Endangered Species Act 
</CENTER>
</H1>

<H3>
<CENTER>
<I>A Comparison of SB 131 and AB 137</I> 
</CENTER>
</H3>

<HR>

<H3>Introduction The California legislature recently began consideration of important proposals to change the manner in which the California Endangered Species Act (CESA) is implemented. The issue of uncompensated takings of private property is squarely addressed in legislation introduced in the Assembly; it is skirted in legislation introduced in the Senate. California, like 42 other states considering some 100 property rights bills, must enact strong legislation to protect the citizens' right in property.</H3>

<P>
Uncompensated regulatory takings are unconstitutional under the just compensation clause of the Fifth Amendment to the United States Constitution, yet such actions are allowed under current law and court rulings in California. Legislative proposals under consideration in California seek to remedy this neglect of constitutional protections.
<P>
A regulatory &quot;taking&quot; is an action of government that reduces or eliminates the value of property through regulation, but the government does not take physical possession of the property. Although guarantees against takings exist in the California Constitution, our courts have been reluctant to protect private property rights.
<P>
Ironically, bureaucratic ignorance and even hostility to these civil rights inevitably lead 
<P>
to the destruction of many species, endangered and threatened, as well as extraordinary losses of critical habitat. When confronted with an endangered species on private property, many
<P>
Americans follow the adage, &quot;Shoot, shovel and shut up.&quot; Search and destroy missions of critical habitat to ward off unwanted endangered species are becoming more common. Jokes about marbled murreletes tasting like something between a spotted owl and a bald eagle loosen up the crowd in Rotary Clubs across the land. Americans, who have been so generous to conservation and preservation organizations, know when their government has gone too far.
<P>
Compensation is constitutionally required, but the courts, the legislature and the bureaucracy have made a mockery of the rights of property owners in California. California is probably the least hospitable of the fifty states to the rights of property owners. Requiring compensation of Californians whose property is diminished by the CESA would restore balance to the debate about which species and which habitats should be saved. Compensation would save many endangered species that are being destroyed by the perverse incentives of the current law. 
<P>
<B>Legislative Approaches to Reforming the California ESA</B>
<P>
Two proposed modifications to the California ESA have been considered by the California legislature. One confronts the issue of compensation head on; the other addresses it only tangentially. AB 137 (Olberg-R-34-Victorville) addresses the perverse consequences of governmental endangered species regulation by aiming to explicitly protect the rights of property owners. By contrast, SB 131 (Maddy-R-14-Fresno) pays much attention to the subject of &quot;biodiversity,&quot; but misses the critical point that property rights are no less important than other fundamental liberties.
<P>
Senator Maddy's bill states: 
<P>
<I>It is the policy of this state to remove disincentives for owners of land and water resources to be good stewards of the land while maximizing the economic return from their property. Therefore, nothing in this chapter shall be applied in a manner that would deny the economically viable use of private property. Furthermore, it is the policy of this state that just compensation be paid to an owner of land or water resources who is denied economically viable use of private property as the result of actions taken by government under this chapter. </I>
<P>
Other than this reference, SB 131 does not mention compensation of property owners victimized by discovery of endangered species on their land. Instead, it provides that a 
<P>
landowner may enter into a &quot;partnership&quot; with the state to protect not only the specific endangered species, but &quot;regional biodiversity.&quot;
<P>
By contrast, AB 137 is very explicit in stating that &quot;just compensation shall be paid for the taking of private or public property, and would, for that purpose, define a 'taking'.&quot; The bill establishes what constitutional lawyers refer to as a &quot;bright line&quot; test. It requires that, 
<P>
<I>Just compensation shall be paid for any taking of private or public property to the owner </I>
<P>
<I>of the property, including compensation for damages incurred by the owner as a result of the taking. For the purposes of this section, the term 'taking of private or public property' means the foreclosure of any use of private property or public property that is otherwise allowed under federal, state, and local law that is caused by any of the following acts if that act, by itself, or in combination with other foreclosures of use so caused, reduces the fair market value of the property by 20 percent or more:</I>
<P>
<I>(a) The inclusion of a species in a list of endangered species or a list of threatened species.</I>
<P>
<I>(b) The designation of a critical habitat for that species.</I>
<P>
<I>(c) The implementation of a recovery plan for that species. </I>
<P>
<I>(d) Any other act that is authorized or required by this chapter.</I>
<P>
What does the language of these bills mean? Does the &quot;policy&quot; announced in Senator Maddy's bill, that just compensation be paid, actually require that compensation be paid? What difference would Assemblyman Olberg's &quot;bright line&quot; definition of a &quot;taking&quot; mean? How does the language of both bills square with the constitutional requirements envisioned by the framers of the United States Constitution and the California Constitution?
<P>
<B>First Principles: Why Protect Property? </B>
<P>
The framers of the U.S. Constitution and the Bill of Rights understood well the importance of protecting private property rights. They believed that it was critical to protect private property for two fundamental reasons: 1) the individual right to property is itself a natural right; 2) the vigorous protection of this right is central to the government's protection of all individual liberties.
<P>
<B>Property as a Natural Right</B>
<P>
Like John Locke, the political thinker from whom many of America's founding principles originate, the founders recognized that individuals are endowed by their creator with the natural right to private property. Both Locke and the founders understood that government is created by man and is granted political authority for the very purpose of protecting natural rights. While many environmentalists would have us believe that private property exists only insofar as it does not interfere with state authority, a look to the Declaration of Independence reveals that they have it backwards: government is only legitimate when it serves the people by making them secure in the exercise of the fundamental natural rights. The Declaration states that, &quot;to secure these rights, governments are instituted among men.&quot;
<P>
<B>Protection of Individual Liberties</B>
<P>
The Declaration of Independence proclaims that the fundamental duty of any just government is to protect the individual natural rights of citizens. James Madison demonstrates, in <I>Federalist</I> 10, how the vigorous protection of private property enables government to live up to this duty.
<P>
Madison writes that the greatest threat to citizens' natural rights are factions, defined as groups of individuals organized for the purpose of attacking the natural rights of their fellow citizens. While he acknowledges that nothing can be done to eliminate factions, Madison argues that they can be controlled, so that no single faction comes to exercise the power of the majority. One of the best ways to keep factions in check, Madison recognizes, is to ensure that there is a great diversity, or &quot;multiplicity,&quot; of interests within society. In this way, no single faction can grow too powerful without being checked and restrained by competing factions.
<P>
How do we ensure that there is such a diversity of interests within society? Madison answers: the vigorous protection of private property. Since individuals, by nature, have different talents and abilities (or &quot;faculties,&quot; as Madison calls them), they will naturally acquire different amounts of property. This diversity of property leads to a diversity of interests, and it is this diversity of interests that is central to controlling factions and protecting individual liberties. Consequently, Madison writes, &quot;The diversity in the faculties 
<P>
of men, from which the rights of property originate,&quot; ensures the diversity of interests necessary to the protection of individual liberties. &quot;The protection of these faculties is the first object of government.&quot;
<P>
Madison's views on property rights were expressed often and eloquently in both private and public writings. He believed property rights were fundamental to all our freedoms:
<P>
<I>[Property]. . . in its</I> <I>particular application, means &quot;that dominion which one man claims and exercises over the external things of the world, in exclusion of every other individual.&quot; In its larger and juster meaning, it embraces everything to which a man may attach a value and have a right; and a man's land, or merchandise, or money, is called his property. In the latter sense, a man has a property in his opinions and the free communication of them. He has a property of peculiar value in his religious opinions, and in the profession and practice dictated by them. He has a property very dear to him in the safety and liberty of his person. He has an equal property in the free use of his faculties, and free choice of the objects on which to employ them</I>. In a word, as a man is said to have a right to his property, he may equally be said to have a property in his rights.<I> </I>[Emphasis added.]
<P>
It is, therefore, through the protection of private property rights that the American political system must fulfill the obligation of the Declaration of Independence. The Fifth Amendment, which holds that private property will not be &quot;taken for public use, without just compensation,&quot; seeks to ensure the government's adherence to the standards of the Declaration.
<P>
Beginning with the Progressive era, the Supreme Court dangerously downgraded the importance of property rights. In so doing, the Court ignored Madison's warning that property rights were central to the protection of individual liberties. Fortunately, more recent courts have slowly come to understand the importance of property rights. In <I>Lynch v. Household Finance</I>, Justice Potter Stewart wrote that, &quot;A fundamental interdependence exists between the personal right to liberty and the personal right in property.&quot; This reflects Madison's understanding of the role of property rights in the American system. Recent Supreme Court decisions do indeed provide hope that the founders' conception of property rights may regain its proper place in the public mind.
<P>
<B>California Courts Embrace Environmental Extremism </B>
<P>
Legislative attempts to protect the environment have led to a body of state jurisprudence concerning the just compensation clause of the Fifth Amendment, and similar provisions in the California Constitution. This jurisprudence is confused and conflicting. Nevertheless, enforcement of environmental laws has spawned &quot;takings&quot; cases that have flooded the courts as more citizens claim harm.
<P>
Some of the recent legal mischief can be traced not to a misreading of the state or federal Constitution but to bad science. Both legislators and judges, understandably, have been influenced by pseudo-science masquerading as evidence of impending environmental catastrophe-the most glaring evidence of which is the loss of species. Fortunately, scientists are beginning to expose the fallacious doomsday claims of the environmentalists. Evidence mounts that much of the environmentalist litany is not only unscientific, but simply untrue. If judges recognized that much of the environmental hysteria is not based on fact, judicial deference to these claims could diminish. Laws based upon the notion that the earth faces imminent catastrophe will change as that view recedes. But courts may be slow to change. Without a change in the law, conforming environmental policy to constitutional mandate is difficult for courts. Conservative jurists normally view such bold steps as judicial activism, while liberal jurists resist them because they are environmentalists.
<P>
Courts in California seem particularly averse to allowing takings claims in matters involving the environment. Citizens affected by confiscatory environmental regulations face nearly impossible procedural obstacles and difficulties, difficulties imposed as a deliberate matter of policy to &quot;protect the public fisc.&quot; These two bills and the escalating public debate over ESA absurdities signal a change in the public attitude, away from extremism and toward a more balanced environmentalism. The question being asked more frequently and more insistently is, does the desirable end of environmental protection require a total disregard for the rights of property owners? The answer we are hearing with increasing volume is, no!
<P>
<B>Just Compensation or &quot;Biodiversity&quot;?</B>
<P>
SB 131 proposes a &quot;partnership&quot; between the landowner and the state, in the event that the landowner is subjected to endangered species legislation. It is difficult to see how Senator Maddy's proposal of &quot;partnerships&quot; between private landowners and the state restores the protection of property established by the founders. We normally think of a partnership as a voluntary association for mutual gain, whereas SB 131 sees the use of property as a privilege bestowed upon the property owner by the state, like a driver's license. 
<P>
An example of this presumption in SB 131 is its embodiment of the planner's view that building and development permits are privileges bestowed by a benevolent state. The costs imposed by the permitting process guarantee that only the wealthy can afford to seek permits. Why do our legislators continue to propose laws that are bound to be specially applied for the benefit of the wealthy? As noted in 1987 by Gideon Kanner, &quot;There's a curious amalgam of radical political rhetoric cheek and jowl with upper middle class exclusivity.&quot; The proposed &quot;public-private partnerships&quot; are but further examples of vehicles for elite patronage.
<P>
The ostensible rationale of the partnership idea is that the owner enters into a contract with the state to serve society's end of &quot;biodiversity.&quot; While &quot;biodiversity,&quot; however defined, may be desirable and important, should this public good transcend and displace the individual's right to use his property or be fully compensated for the loss of that right? Surely Maddy's bill is a step toward recognition of some rights in property, however exclusive, and may even be attractive to large developers who are stymied by the current regulatory regime. They may buy their way out of regulation with minimal harm. After all, they can pass on the costs of Maddy's &quot;partnership&quot; to their customers. But it does little to help the small landowner or developer.
<P>
SB 131 does contain a <I>de minimis</I> five acre exception to application of the CESA. But what of his neighbor who owns 5.1 acres? Are his rights less important? Either property rights are important all the time and for all Americans, or they are not important at all.
<P>
SB 131 also provides assurances that no person's right to &quot;economically use&quot; his property may be taken without just compensation. This is an illusory gesture. Just what is economical use of property in California? The California courts have provided no guidance and the issue is one of the most pithy problems in the jurisprudence of regulatory takings. The Supreme Court has established that reasonable, investment-backed expectations may not be taken by overregulation. Anyone familiar with the manner in which land use laws are applied in this state knows that the &quot;discovery&quot; of endangered species can (and often does) follow down-zoning and general plan amendments, and perhaps several permit denials, each of which devalue the property. From which devaluation does the taking occur? At what point does one's reasonable &quot;investment-backed expectation&quot; occur? Furthermore, there is little judicial support for the idea that economic use necessarily means the highest and best use. Currently, the Supreme Court's property rights jurisprudence protects only against regulation that takes <I>all</I> use of the property. 
<P>
Finally, SB 131 appears to allow for concurrent use of property by humans and endangered species, but under the watchful eye of the state. Under this scheme, there is no taking if some corner of the property is left for a business use, while the balance is preserved in a state supervised natural condition. SB 131 does not correct the deficiencies in the current law, and confounds an already confused mix of cases and laws. The promise of &quot;just compensation&quot; is not a right under this scheme, but a privilege that may be conferred at the will of the sovereign. 
<P>
One must conclude, reluctantly, that the approach of SB 131 to the California Endangered Species Act is to dilute some objectionable aspects of the current law while paying lip service to property rights. It is a <I>political </I>approach, one designed to placate large developers who have been effectively shut down under our current regulatory scheme, and to satisfy environmentalists bent on the new buzz word in their business, &quot;biodiversity.&quot; However, it ignores the fundamental problem facing ordinary Californians seeking security in the enjoyment of their natural rights. California does not honor citizens' rights in property today, and under Senator Maddy's bill, it will not honor them tomorrow.
<P>
<B>Defining Takings-Does it Help?</B>
<P>
Assemblyman Olberg takes an entirely different approach to endangered species legislative reform. Rather than establish a new bureaucracy to determine the compatibility of humans and endangered species, Olberg's bill assumes the preeminence of property rights over environmental concerns. Simply put, his bill requires compensation whenever the presence of an endangered species diminishes the value of property by a factor of 20 percent or more.
<P>
The simplicity of Olberg's bill is attractive because it clarifies two issues that have confounded the courts in regulatory takings cases: first, that property rights are preeminent over the worthy legislative efforts of the state; and second, that a regulatory taking is defined by a predetermined event. Assuming that some burden on the landowner is fair, AB 137 burdens his property up to and including 20 percent of its value. Thus a 20 percent loss is the bright line beyond which CESA regulation may not go. 
<P>
One problem with Olberg's &quot;bright line&quot; approach is that it fails to remove the environmental disincentives of the current law. It is human nature to avoid obligations imposed by the state. Whether the loss to regulation is 10 percent, 20 percent or more, the citizen still has some incentives to &quot;shoot, shovel and shut up&quot; if an endangered species inhabits his property. Thus the burden on the individual is not only counterproductive to the end of the regulation, but also punishes the citizen for events over which he has no control.
<P>
Another problem of AB 137 is that it fails to identify the date of valuation of the property. Endangered species are often &quot;discovered&quot; only upon application for a development permit. Does the 20 percent devaluation occur before or after the discovery, before or after the application?
<P>
Finally, both bills fail to adequately address two serious deficiencies in current ESA law: legislation can only meet the standards of the rule of law if it can be applied <I>generally</I> <I>and equally</I> to the whole population and if its enforcement is <I>predictable and certain</I>, not arbitrary or capricious. If a citizen must bear the cost of the presence of an animal that resides (however temporarily or seasonally) on his property, then that citizen is being regulated while his neighbor is not. The presence of the animal is <I>not </I>predictable, and the application of the law is therefore uncertain. If some (large) land owners can buy their way out of the compliance while others cannot, then the law is again uncertain. Under a uniform system of just compensation, the whole society will bear the cost of purchasing the land where the animal resides. This meets the test of the rule of law, and is also just and fair, since it is the whole society, through government policy, that is deriving benefit from the protection of the animal. 
<P>
<B>Reaffirming the Preeminence of Property Rights</B>
<P>
Assemblyman Olberg's requirement of compensation, establishing the preeminence of property rights over endangered species, is a huge improvement over current law. AB 137 accomplishes this simply, indeed elegantly. Under current law, endangered species regulation is imposed with impunity because there is no cost to the state or any other interested party that brings a lawsuit under the endangered species law; the property owner bears the entire burden.
<P>
If the philosophy behind AB 137 were enacted, the state would have to evaluate the full impact of endangered species regulation on a case by case basis. An ancillary benefit of requiring compensation would be that endangered species would be protected on the basis of rational inquiry, with a view to the protection of the rights of individual citizens. No longer would the cry that the environment is on the verge of collapse mandate the suspension of &quot;mere&quot; economic rights. 
<P>
This is not to say that wildlife preservation will be abandoned under a fair compensatory scheme. In fact, it would most likely be enhanced. One need only look at society's slavish attempt to recycle trash to recognize its commitment to nature and its moral desire to preserve the natural environment. Requiring compensation for the imposition of this environmental regulation will only enhance the opportunities for preservation. Compensation should virtually eliminate the &quot;shoot, shovel and shut up&quot; phenomenon because private efforts to preserve endangered species would be given an impetus not found under current law.
<P>
<B>CONCLUSION</B>
<P>
If enacted, bills like SB 131 or the legislation that is certain to follow it would advance an already confused and unfair jurisprudence of regulatory takings cases. They would not help the average property owner. Moreover, such laws could be the Trojan Horse within which hide a new horde of regulations on &quot;biodiversity&quot; as well as more federal incursions into state affairs.
<P>
Despite its elegant brevity, AB 137 could be improved. As the legislature considers AB 137, it should attempt to incorporate the following measures into the ultimate legislation. At minimum, a compensation scheme should include the following:
<UL>
<LI>A declaration of condemnation should be required of a state agency invoking the CESA, in a court of competent jurisdiction near the situs of the taking. If the state wishes to impose its will to the detriment of the individual, it should be incumbent upon the state to initiate the compensation action, and to do so in the area affected by the law. <FONT SIZE=2></FONT>
<LI>Partial and temporary takings should be fully compensated. <FONT SIZE=2></FONT>
<LI>Compensation should occur when the regulation is imposed, and the value of the land should be taken into account at that time, given the owner's reasonable, individual expectations for the development potential of the land. <FONT SIZE=2></FONT>
<LI>Nothing in the compensatory scheme should prevent citizen claims under the common law doctrine of inverse condemnation, which allows individuals to seek remedy for uncompensated takings. If the government does not follow the law, a citizen should be able to initiate the process of compensation. However, a citizen subject to endangered species regulation should not have to endure the costly and time-consuming expense of pursuing an administrative mandamus claim as a prerequisite to his claim for damages. <FONT SIZE=2></FONT>
<LI>Separation of the real property estate on ecological grounds should be permitted where fair to the landowner. A severable environmental interest similar to the mineral estate, water resources, and other severable interests should be permitted to avoid total takings. This should save the government some funds while allowing continued use of the affected lands. <FONT SIZE=2></FONT>
<LI>At their option, individuals should be able to avoid condemnation of their land under application of the ESA. At the option of the land owner, he should be able to preserve critical habitat himself. Appropriate property tax incentives should be allowed to encourage the creation and preservation of habitat and to avoid the condemnation of private lands. This would become possible if the environmental estate were granted legal recognition. <FONT SIZE=2></FONT>
<LI>Individuals should receive appropriate income tax benefits for grants of critical habitat to private, tax-exempt conservation organizations. Individuals who may not be able to take advantage of tax deductions should be able to sell their land that is burdened with critical habitat to private conservation organizations without incurring income tax liability on &quot;gain&quot; they may receive. If these measures are enacted, critical habitat will become a very marketable asset instead of a blight. Further, encouragement of private protection of critical habitat in lieu of direct government compensation will avoid depletion of the treasury, discourage government ownership of formerly private lands, and ensure proper stewardship of habitat.
</UL>

<P>
These steps are necessary to fulfill the objectives of an ordered system of liberty that observes all Constitutional rights and recognizes their interrelatedness. While AB 137 nearly reaches the mark, our Legislature should adopt a bolder vision, and ensure that property rights in California are not forgotten.
<CENTER>
- Robert J. Ernst III* 
</CENTER>
Adjunct Fellow in Environmental Policy
<HR>
<I>* Robert J. Ernst III is an attorney in private practice in Monterey County, California. He speaks and writes widely on environmental and land use issues.</I> 
