<head><title>John Baden, Chairman of FREE</title></head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" BACKGROUND="/free/bluewhite_paper.gif">
<P><IMG ALIGN="left" hspace="5"
 SRC="/free/Images/Baden.photo.jpeg" 
ALT="John A. Baden">
<h1>John A. Baden, Ph. D.</h1>

<hr> 
John Baden is founder and chairman of the Foundation for Research on 
Economics and the Environment (FREE).  FREE is a 501 (c)(3) 
market-oriented research and education foundation.  The main 
FREE office is in Bozeman, Montana and a second is in Seattle, 
Washington.  Dr. Baden is a leader in developing the New Resource 
Economics, an incentive-based approach to environmental and 
natural resource management that stresses private property rights 
and the market process as policy instruments.</P><P>
Dr. Baden received his Ph.D. from Indiana University in 1969 and 
then was awarded a National Science Foundation Postdoctoral 
Fellowship in environmental policy.  He has held endowed 
professorships, received teaching awards and is the author or 
editor of seven books, numerous articles on energy and natural 
resources, and a syndicated column originating in The Seattle Times.  
</P><P>John Baden is a member of the Mont Pelerin Society, has 
served two terms on the National Petroleum Council, and has served 
as President of the Association of Private Enterprise Education.  
He recently resigned his Affiliate Professorship at the University 
of Washington School of Business to devote his full attention to FREE.  
For the past four years he has organized a series of four week-long
 seminars in environmental economics and policy for federal judges.
</P><P>Dr. Baden and his wife, Professor Ramona Marotz-Baden, both 
avid <A HREF="Images/biker.gif">bicyclists</A>, own and operate a 
ranch in the Gallatin Valley of Montana and an orchard in the Yakima 
Valley of Washington. </P>

